{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Consumers are able to purchase cars that have deadly defects and sellers have few obligations to disclose the defects to them....", "abstract": "Visit by New York Times reporters to used-car auction in Queens finds that half of 20 cars being auctioned had been recalled for various reasons, but had not been fixed; episode highlights how consumers can easily purchase cars with deadly defects without being informed by sellers, who are not required by federal law to disclose safety recalls or fix dangerous defects.", "section_name": "Business Day", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Rachel", "role": "reported", "lastname": "ABRAMS", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}, {"firstname": "Hiroko", "role": "reported", "lastname": "TABUCHI", "rank": 2, "organization": ""}], "original": "By RACHEL ABRAMS and HIROKO TABUCHI"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/27/business/at-auction-vehicles-with-fatal-flaws.html", "lead_paragraph": "Consumers are able to purchase cars that have deadly defects and sellers have few obligations to disclose the defects to them.", "headline": {"main": "Buying at a Used Car Auction? What You Don\u2019t Know Could Kill You", "print_headline": "No Bargain for Buyers"}, "_id": "5811404b95d0e022439c56d7", "word_count": "856", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/10/27/business/27AUCTION-1/27AUCTION-1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/10/27/business/27AUCTION-1/27AUCTION-1-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2016/10/27/business/27AUCTION-1/27AUCTION-1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/10/27/business/27AUCTION-1/27AUCTION-1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "400"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2016/10/27/business/27AUCTION-1/27AUCTION-1-thum